        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1980-10-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-10-24T12:30:00-05:00" n="30" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d30">
                <head>30. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Leonid <persName corresp="#p_BLI_1">Brezhnev</persName>, General Secretary of the
                    Communist Party of the Soviet Union, visited Washington for a summit with
                    President Richard <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName> June 18–25,
                    1973. Discussion of the strategic arms limitation talks was limited, if not
                    tangential, to discussions of an agreement between the United States and the
                    Soviet Union on the prevention of nuclear war. President <persName
                        corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName> indicated his desire to steer
                    conversations toward the subject of <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> in
                    his meeting with <persName corresp="#p_BLI_1">Brezhnev</persName> on June 18,
                    12:35–3:15 p.m. According to the memorandum of conversation, the President
                    stated: “Let me close with two brief points. One is the very historic agreement
                    that we will sign on Friday. It will be seen as more words than substance unless
                    we can move along on <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss>. I hope we can talk
                    about moving <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> along.” On June 20, during a
                    meeting at Camp David, <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName> raised the
                    subject of the <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> principles that <persName
                        corresp="#p_BLI_1">Brezhnev</persName> had handed to Henry <persName
                        corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>, the President’s Assistant for
                    National Security Affairs, during his visit to Moscow in early May (see <ref
                        target="#d24">Document 24</ref>). <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1"
                        >Nixon</persName> told <persName corresp="#p_BLI_1">Brezhnev</persName> that
                    he hoped they could include in the priciples 1974 as a goal for completing a
                    SALT II agreement. <persName corresp="#p_BLI_1">Brezhnev</persName> responded
                    with a joke that <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName> and Soviet
                    Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DAF_1">Anatoly Dobrynin</persName> had also
                    left the question open. On June 21, the Basic Principles of Negotiations on the
                    Further Limitation of Strategic Arms was signed by <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1"
                        >Nixon</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_BLI_1">Brezhnev</persName>; ten
                    additional agreements on other U.S.-Soviet issues were also signed during the
                    summit. The Basic Principles reiterated that both the United States and Soviet
                    Union were committed to the May 1972 agreements and asserted that active
                    negotiations toward a permanent agreement would continue, with the hope of
                    concluding such an agreement in 1974. The full texts of all memoranda of
                    conversation between <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_BLI_1">Brezhnev</persName> are printed in <ref
                        target="frus1969-76v15">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, Vol. XV, Soviet Union,
                        June 1972–August 1974</ref>. The full text of the <gloss target="#t_SALT_1"
                        >SALT</gloss> Basic Principles is in Department of State <hi rend="italic"
                        >Bulletin</hi>, July 23, 1973, p. 158.</p>
